61406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcancr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ghea"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Health</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcancr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gmed"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Medical Conditions</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcancr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Science</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Cancer patient's remarkable journey; 'Accidental scan' revealed tumour</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>It was her worst nightmare come true.</Para><Para>National Neuroscience Institute principal radiographer Oh Hui Ping, 34, had roped in her younger brother Zhi Long to do a trial run on a new MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) machine at the institute.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>But as she moved the mouse controlling which part of the brain was being scanned, she came across a white patch in the image that stood out among the grey mass of the brain.</Para><Para>Her thoughts were in turmoil.</Para><Para>"What is that? Is it a tumour? Is it malignant? What are these changes in the white matter of the brain?" she recalled, the questions tumbling out one after another as a feeling of dread came over her.</Para><Para>Mr Oh, an auditor, 32, was immediately sent for more tests which confirmed the bad news - he had a medium-sized tumour in the left frontal lobe, a critical part of the brain involved in movement, language, decision making, emotions and personality.</Para><Para>"I'm a healthcare professional, I couldn't cry in front of Zhi Long or my family. I could show my fear and my emotions only when I went home to my husband," said Ms Oh. "But it was extremely stressful."</Para><Para>The family - father, retired storeman Oh Han Kok, 57; mother Seng Kiah Eng, 57, a housewife; Ms Oh and sister Hui Shan, 30, a dental hygienist - were all there to give their love and support when Mr Oh was wheeled into the operating theatre just days later. And they were waiting with relieved smiles when he was wheeled back out after the successful operation.</Para><Para>Of the experience, which lasted over four hours, Mr Oh remembers very little.</Para><Para>"For my first surgery, it was quite a major one," he told The Straits Times, speaking from his family's five-room flat in Woodlands. "I feel like there was some loss to my short-term memory, and there were some things I said which I can't recall.</Para><Para>"It took about two weeks to feel back to normal."</Para><Para>But thanks to his family and the support of his employer KPMG, which gave him time off to recover, he has done well after 30 radiotherapy sessions and eight months of chemotherapy.</Para><Para>The silver lining - the "accidental scan" had detected the cancerous and potentially aggressive lump even before Mr Oh had concrete symptoms, which could eventually show up as behavioural changes, memory loss and paralysis.</Para><Para>So he received treatment fast.</Para><Para>Said Ms Oh: "There were a lot of ups and downs, but the end result was that he got the malignant cancer out."</Para><Para>The experience was also a bonding experience for the three siblings, who are now closer than ever, she added.</Para><Para>Their sister had ferried him to his various treatments and she herself had been there for all the consultations, while their parents cooked his meals and helped take care of his prized marine clownfish which he had bred at home.</Para><Para>Asked why he had agreed to allow The Straits Times to document the whole procedure, Mr Oh said: "Brain cancer is underfunded, and I hope to create awareness about it.</Para><Para>"If by doing so, it can help people recover faster, why not?"</Para><Para>Chang Ai-Lien</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Chang Ai-Lien </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Oh Zhi Long, 32, undergoing awake surgery in TTSH. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

